properties.description: The intention of hole 1 is to drive your ball over the creek guarding the first landing area to an open fairway shaped by tightly mown swales of Zorro Zoysia grass which hides a low approach to the first green. On the left is a massive Mackenzie-styled bunkers shared with the 10th green.

A drivable par-four if you carry the ball over a collection of 3 bunkers on the right, which will then roll down towards a small green. However, any attempt that veers left will likely meet with a watery end as the fairway slopes sharp and narrow towards a creek running along the hole.

An uphill par-four with a majestic waterfall in the backdrop, the difficulty of this hole is the approach to an uphill inverted green site where the landing zone is imperceptible. A bunker awaits, short left and anything off line or short will see the ball roll back down.

An elevated tee box makes this short par-three a fun shootout. Surrounded by a panoramic view of metropolitan Singapore, the Southern Islands and the iconic Marina Bay Sands in the distance, the shot to the green must be accurate as there is no bailout area.

This first par-five of the front nine, the first landing area is guarded by two bunkers on the right and  the left side is flanked by a long lake feature winding its way up from tee to green. With a narrow fairway to negotiate and an almost full island green that juts out into the lake with three bunkers to its right, it takes a confident shot to approach this hole in two.

Hole-six plays east and up towards the Pyramid with a magnificent view of Mount Serapong in the background. The landing area is well guarded on the right with a grouping of bunkers. The challenge of the approach is to avoid the cluster of bunkers surrounding a raised green; this green complex makes for a fair challenge for the short game.

The longest par-three on the golf course, it features a creek running down the left hand side towards the green and joins with a lake behind. The safe play is towards the right as a bunker sidles between the green and the creek on the left, especially when the winds pick up around here.

A long par-five that tests your long game as well as your nerve. A very narrow fairway that winds around a lake on the left and dense forest on the right. The incentive here is to hit it long but place the shot to the left for any chance to reach the green. The fairway narrows towards the green.

The majesty of the MacKenzie bunkers is in full view here at this long and challenging uphill par-four. A large fairway bunker surrounds the large landing area to give you an opportunity to reach a deceiving green with a false front, giving you an illusion that is closer than you realise.

Another hole that runs parallel, this time it is to the 1st. Separated only by a cluster of trees and sharing the same oversized bunker, hole ten is a straightforward par-four, however, you need to be accurate on the approach shot to a small green with strong undulation to protect par.

Fairway bunkers protect the right on this hole but a decent drive should make that avoidable. The fairway undulates greatly so a sidehill or downhill lie may make the approach to a green that inverts sharply to the left a difficult shot to make.

Long hitters should take the Tiger line above the tall ficus tree to a fairly wide fairway for a shorter approach to the green on this downhill dogleg right hole. A waste bunker lines all through the left with a green shielded by a daunting pot bunker in front.

A dog leg left par-five, the tee shot here is key with bunkers left and right protecting the landing zone. Tee up short for safety or go long and centre, short of the bunkers, for a look at the green. A heroic approach could get you there in two but be careful; a deceivingly elevated green will skittle overhit shots as it falls away to the back.

A seemingly simple par-four with a generously wide fairway, however, the tree lined tee complex forces you to hit a straight shot out of the blocks, the challenge here is to select the correct club and yardage as a bunker just short of the green presents an optical illusion of a hole playing longer than it seems. False fronts compound the difficulty so it is better to be long than short here.

A tricky par-three with a sneaky green that falls fast towards the water on the left and defended by a large bunker. Pin position on any given day will make the difference here, making shot selection a prime consideration.

From the back, the tee shot is compounded by a carry over a stream that flows all through to an island green. Two large bunkers cramp a narrow fairway between two landing zones so the safe play is to the right, especially for long hitters. Another bunker sits between the second landing area and green, if you plan to go for it in two you must stop your ball on the redan shaped green.

A continuously long, snaking tee box means the hole can play differently on any given day for any tee position. Off the back, the challenge is to carry a water hazard and bunker protecting the green, especially if the pin is well back and left.

Aim for the clock tower atop the Clubhouse as you set up your tee shot here and take the left side.  As with many holes in the golf course, the challenge is in the approach shot as a collection of spectacular Mackenzie-styled bunkers cover the area on the right.
